<ArticleLayout
  title="Laundry Essentials for Australian Homes"
  description="The laundry equipment that earns its place, from baskets and drying space to stain care, pegs and a clear area for folding."
  category="Laundry"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="8 minute read"
  image="/images/laundry.webp"
  imageAlt="A practical laundry room with warm finishes, baskets and tidy everyday storage"
>
  <p>
    Laundry essentials reveal themselves during a difficult load: a basket handle digs into a
    hand, school clothes need drying before morning, or there is nowhere clean to fold a towel.
    Those moments are more reliable than a long list of products sold as must-haves.
  </p>
  <p>
    Follow one load from hamper to cupboard and note what the household reaches for. Most homes
    need a way to collect clothes, carry them, wash them, dry them and deal with stains. Ironing,
    steaming, sorting and pet washing depend far more on the household.
  </p>
  <p>
    Choose equipment for those repeated jobs and give each item a place between uses. A compact
    laundry with a sound basket and dependable drying plan can work better than a large room
    crowded with accessories.
  </p>

  <h2>Follow one load from hamper to cupboard</h2>
  <p>
    Notice how washing actually moves through the home.
  </p>
  <p>A typical laundry routine may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Collecting dirty clothes.</li>
    <li>Sorting washing.</li>
    <li>Treating stains.</li>
    <li>Washing clothes.</li>
    <li>Drying indoors or outdoors.</li>
    <li>Folding.</li>
    <li>Ironing or steaming.</li>
    <li>Returning clothes to bedrooms.</li>
    <li>Washing towels, sheets and pet items.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The right setup depends on the household. A family may need multiple hampers and larger
    drying space. A single-person household may only need one hamper and a compact drying
    rack. A rental or apartment may need flexible storage that does not require drilling.
  </p>
  <p>
    The goal is to reduce friction in the routine, not add products that complicate the room
    or create another place for washing to stall.
  </p>

  <h2>Use hampers that suit how washing is sorted</h2>
  <p>
    A laundry hamper is one of the most important laundry basics because it shapes where
    dirty clothes wait. It should be easy to use, easy to move and the right size for the
    household.
  </p>
  <p>Useful hamper options include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>One large hamper.</li>
    <li>Separate hampers for lights and darks.</li>
    <li>A hamper for towels.</li>
    <li>A hamper for children's clothes.</li>
    <li>A small delicates basket.</li>
    <li>A slim hamper for small spaces.</li>
    <li>A hamper with handles.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Separate hampers can help if the household already sorts washing by colour, fabric or
    person. But too many hampers can also take up space and create clutter.
  </p>
  <p>
    For small laundries, a slim vertical hamper or collapsible basket may work better than a
    wide laundry basket.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep laundry baskets practical</h2>
  <p>
    Laundry baskets are useful for carrying clean washing, hanging clothes outside and moving
    items between rooms.
  </p>
  <p>When choosing a laundry basket, consider:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Size.</li>
    <li>Weight when full.</li>
    <li>Handle comfort.</li>
    <li>Whether it stacks.</li>
    <li>Whether it fits near the machine.</li>
    <li>Whether it is easy to wipe clean.</li>
    <li>Whether it suits outdoor drying if used.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A large basket may hold more washing, but it can become heavy and awkward. Two medium
    baskets may work better than one oversized basket for some homes.
  </p>
  <p>
    Stackable baskets can save space when not in use.
  </p>

  <h2>Create a place for detergents and washing products</h2>
  <p>
    Laundry products should be easy to access but safely stored.
  </p>
  <p>Common laundry products include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Laundry detergent.</li>
    <li>Fabric softener if used.</li>
    <li>Stain remover.</li>
    <li>Soaker.</li>
    <li>Delicates wash.</li>
    <li>Washing machine cleaner.</li>
    <li>Pegs.</li>
    <li>Lint roller.</li>
    <li>Mesh wash bags.</li>
    <li>Cleaning cloths.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Store these items together where possible. A shelf, cupboard, basket or caddy can stop
    bottles and packets from spreading across the bench or floor.
  </p>
  <p>
    In homes with children or pets, laundry chemicals should be stored securely and out of
    reach.
  </p>

  <h2>Use a stain treatment area</h2>
  <p>
    Stains are easier to manage when stain products are easy to find. A small stain treatment
    area can be useful, especially in households with children, uniforms, work clothes, sports
    gear or pets.
  </p>
  <p>A basic stain setup may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Stain remover.</li>
    <li>Small brush.</li>
    <li>Soaking bucket.</li>
    <li>Gloves.</li>
    <li>Old towel or cloth.</li>
    <li>Mesh bags for delicate items.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    This does not need much space. A small basket or shelf section near the washing machine
    may be enough.
  </p>
  <p>
    Avoid letting soaking buckets sit in walkways or areas where they can be knocked over.
  </p>

  <h2>Add drying options that suit the home</h2>
  <p>
    Drying is often the hardest part of laundry organisation. Some homes have outdoor
    clotheslines, while others rely on indoor drying racks, balconies, dryers or shared drying
    spaces.
  </p>
  <p>Useful drying options include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Outdoor clothesline.</li>
    <li>Foldable drying rack.</li>
    <li>Wall-mounted drying rack.</li>
    <li>Over-door drying rack.</li>
    <li>Peg basket.</li>
    <li>Coat hangers.</li>
    <li>Dryer balls if using a dryer.</li>
    <li>Indoor airer for wet weather.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A foldable drying rack is useful because it can be packed away when not needed.
    Wall-mounted options can save floor space, but they may not suit rentals unless
    installation is allowed.
  </p>
  <p>
    For humid or wet weather, indoor drying needs ventilation. Clothes left in closed rooms
    can take longer to dry and may make the space feel damp.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep pegs easy to find</h2>
  <p>
    Pegs are small but important if the home uses an outdoor clothesline or balcony drying
    setup.
  </p>
  <p>Good peg storage options include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Peg basket.</li>
    <li>Peg bag.</li>
    <li>Small plastic tub.</li>
    <li>Hook near the door.</li>
    <li>Basket beside the laundry machine.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Keep pegs near where they are used. If the clothesline is outside, a peg bag that can hang
    on the line may be more useful than storing pegs deep inside a cupboard.
  </p>
  <p>
    Choose pegs that suit the local conditions. In coastal areas, some materials may wear out
    faster from sun, salt and weather exposure.
  </p>

  <h2>Use mesh wash bags for small and delicate items</h2>
  <p>
    Mesh wash bags can help protect small or delicate items and stop them from disappearing
    through the laundry cycle.
  </p>
  <p>They can be useful for:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Socks.</li>
    <li>Underwear.</li>
    <li>Bras.</li>
    <li>Delicates.</li>
    <li>Baby items.</li>
    <li>Reusable cloths.</li>
    <li>Face washers.</li>
    <li>Small pet items.</li>
    <li>Sports accessories.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Keeping mesh bags near the hamper or washing machine makes them more likely to be used.
  </p>
  <p>
    A small set in different sizes is usually enough for most households.
  </p>

  <h2>Make folding easier</h2>
  <p>
    Clean washing often becomes clutter when there is nowhere to fold it. A clear folding area
    can make the laundry routine easier to finish.
  </p>
  <p>Possible folding areas include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Laundry bench.</li>
    <li>Dining table.</li>
    <li>Bed.</li>
    <li>Portable folding board if used.</li>
    <li>Clean basket system.</li>
    <li>A cleared section of a spare room.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Not every laundry has bench space. In small homes, the main goal is to move clean washing
    to a consistent folding spot rather than letting it sit in baskets for days.
  </p>
  <p>
    A simple system can help: one basket for clean washing, one for items to put away and one
    for ironing or repairs.
  </p>

  <h2>Store ironing or steaming items neatly</h2>
  <p>
    Not every household irons regularly, but if ironing or steaming is part of the routine,
    those items need a clear place.
  </p>
  <p>Useful ironing storage may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Ironing board.</li>
    <li>Iron or garment steamer.</li>
    <li>Heat-resistant mat.</li>
    <li>Spray bottle.</li>
    <li>Hangers.</li>
    <li>Storage hook for the ironing board.</li>
    <li>Small basket for ironing supplies.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A wall hook or cupboard slot can stop the ironing board from leaning awkwardly against a
    wall.
  </p>
  <p>
    If ironing is rare, keep the setup compact. If work uniforms or business clothes are used
    often, it may be worth keeping ironing items easier to access.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep cleaning tools contained</h2>
  <p>
    Many laundries double as the cleaning storage area. Mops, brooms, buckets, sprays and
    cloths can quickly make the room feel messy.
  </p>
  <p>Useful cleaning storage options include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Wall-mounted broom holder.</li>
    <li>Tall cupboard.</li>
    <li>Hooks.</li>
    <li>Cleaning caddy.</li>
    <li>Bucket storage.</li>
    <li>Shelf baskets.</li>
    <li>Cloth basket.</li>
    <li>Separate area for spare cleaning products.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Keep frequently used cleaning items within reach and bulk supplies higher, lower or further
    back.
  </p>
  <p>
    Cleaning products should be stored safely and clearly. Avoid mixing unrelated chemicals or
    keeping leaking bottles in cupboards.
  </p>

  <h2>Add hooks for quick storage</h2>
  <p>
    Hooks are useful in laundries because they provide quick storage without needing large
    furniture.
  </p>
  <p>Laundry hooks can hold:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Reusable shopping bags.</li>
    <li>Cleaning cloths.</li>
    <li>Peg bags.</li>
    <li>Pet leads.</li>
    <li>Aprons.</li>
    <li>Ironing board.</li>
    <li>Laundry bags.</li>
    <li>Delicates bags.</li>
    <li>Small brushes.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    For renters, removable hooks may be useful, but check surfaces carefully because adhesives
    can damage paint or tiles when removed.
  </p>
  <p>
    Hooks work best when used for a few specific items. Too many overloaded hooks can make the
    laundry feel cluttered.
  </p>

  <h2>Use shelves and baskets for vertical storage</h2>
  <p>
    Laundry walls are often underused. Shelves can create storage without taking up floor
    space.
  </p>
  <p>Shelves and baskets can hold:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Detergent.</li>
    <li>Cleaning supplies.</li>
    <li>Toilet paper.</li>
    <li>Spare cloths.</li>
    <li>Light bulbs.</li>
    <li>Batteries.</li>
    <li>Pet items.</li>
    <li>Laundry bags.</li>
    <li>Bulk household supplies.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Use baskets to contain smaller items. This makes open shelves look calmer and makes it
    easier to pull items down safely.
  </p>
  <p>
    Heavy products should not be stored too high. Keep heavier bottles and bulk supplies lower
    where they are easier and safer to lift.
  </p>

  <h2>Think about pet laundry needs</h2>
  <p>
    Homes with pets may need extra laundry storage for pet towels, blankets, leads, grooming
    items or cleaning supplies.
  </p>
  <p>Useful pet laundry storage may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Separate basket for pet towels.</li>
    <li>Hook for leads.</li>
    <li>Small tub for grooming items.</li>
    <li>Storage for pet stain cleaner.</li>
    <li>Area for drying wet pet items.</li>
    <li>Washable mat near the laundry door.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Keeping pet items separate can stop them mixing with household towels and clothes.
  </p>
  <p>
    If the laundry opens to the yard, this area can also be useful for muddy paws, wet towels
    and outdoor pet gear.
  </p>

  <h2>Manage spare household supplies</h2>
  <p>
    The laundry often becomes the place for spare household items. This can be useful, but
    only if the storage is controlled.
  </p>
  <p>Common spare supplies include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Toilet paper.</li>
    <li>Paper towel.</li>
    <li>Cleaning refills.</li>
    <li>Soap refills.</li>
    <li>Bin liners.</li>
    <li>Batteries.</li>
    <li>Light bulbs.</li>
    <li>Cloths.</li>
    <li>Sponges.</li>
    <li>Pet supplies.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A labelled basket or shelf section for backup items can make it easier to see what is
    already in the home before buying more.
  </p>
  <p>
    Avoid letting backup supplies block access to the washing machine, sink or cleaning tools.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep the sink area clear</h2>
  <p>
    If the laundry has a sink, it should remain usable. Laundry sinks are useful for soaking,
    rinsing, cleaning buckets, handwashing clothes and dealing with messy household jobs.
  </p>
  <p>Try not to permanently fill the sink with:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Buckets.</li>
    <li>Dirty shoes.</li>
    <li>Cleaning cloths.</li>
    <li>Random household items.</li>
    <li>Pet bowls.</li>
    <li>Soaking clothes left too long.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A clear sink makes the laundry more functional. If items often land in the sink, they may
    need a separate basket or shelf.
  </p>

  <h2>Before adding another laundry item</h2>
  <p>Before buying laundry products, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Laundry size.</li>
    <li>Machine position.</li>
    <li>Door swing.</li>
    <li>Whether there is bench space.</li>
    <li>Whether there is wall space.</li>
    <li>Whether drilling is allowed if renting.</li>
    <li>Ventilation.</li>
    <li>Outdoor drying access.</li>
    <li>How many people use the laundry.</li>
    <li>Whether the product is easy to clean.</li>
    <li>Whether it solves a real daily problem.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Small laundries benefit from compact, flexible products. Large storage units may make the
    space harder to use if they block movement.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before adding storage around appliances, check the
    <a href="/guides/washing-machine-and-dryer-space-what-to-measure-before-buying-storage/">washing machine and dryer measurements</a>
    that keep doors, hoses, filters and ventilation accessible.
  </p>

  <h2>What a well-equipped laundry really means</h2>
  <p>
    A good laundry is not built from a full matching set. It is built from the few items
    that remove the biggest points of friction.
  </p>
  <p>
    Hampers, baskets, drying racks, hooks, shelves, mesh bags and cleaning caddies can all be
    useful when they solve a real problem. Deal first with the part of the routine that causes the
    most frustration, then improve one area at a time instead of filling the room at once.
  </p>

